00:01:27.929 --> 00:01:30.103
 And remember that the temperature is proportional 

00:01:30.103 --> 00:01:32.094
 of the average kinetic energy. 

00:01:32.094 --> 00:01:34.532
 And those who were just burning, 

00:01:34.532 --> 00:01:36.767
 or molecules just downstream of the reaction, 

00:01:36.767 --> 00:01:38.636
 or perhaps those who were part of the reaction, 

00:01:38.640 --> 00:01:43.420
 will have very high average kinetic energy, 

00:01:43.420 --> 00:01:47.160
 because this burning reaction released all this energy. 

00:01:47.160 --> 00:01:50.054
 And then they will hit other molecules, 

00:01:50.060 --> 00:01:52.960
 who may not have such high kinetic energy, 

00:01:52.960 --> 00:01:55.460
 but then they will transfer that kinetic energy 

00:01:55.460 --> 00:01:57.180
 through these collisions. 

00:01:57.180 --> 00:01:59.280
 And we have a whole video about the thermal performance, 

00:01:59.280 --> 00:02:00.559
 but that's what's happening. 

00:02:00.560 --> 00:02:02.020
 Things with high kinetic energy 

00:02:02.020 --> 00:02:03.951
 are thrown into things with lower kinetic energy 

00:02:03.951 --> 00:02:06.025
 and transfer some of that kinetic energy 

00:02:06.025 --> 00:02:07.872
 and transfer part of this impulse. 

00:02:07.880 --> 00:02:11.840
 This is definitely the case when we look at such a fire, 

00:02:11.840 --> 00:02:15.040
 neighboring molecules are pushed into other molecules 

00:02:15.040 --> 00:02:16.980
 and transfer energy. 

